  "content": "\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan class=\"h-card\" translate=\"no\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://hachyderm.io/@markd\" class=\"u-url mention\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e@\u003cspan\u003emarkd\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e \u003cspan class=\"h-card\" translate=\"no\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://infosec.exchange/@sudorandom\" class=\"u-url mention\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e@\u003cspan\u003esudorandom\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e 1. I never use TryGo. I just use Go.\u003cbr\u003e2. I am a strong believer in structured concurrency. I have been using Go for over 10 years and in my experience, approximately no one can write correct non-trivial code using channels and select.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eI recommend newcomers to categorically *never use channels and raw goroutines*. context and errgroup are more than enough for 90% of use cases.\u003c/p\u003e",
